WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:24.840
CHAP. XIII. Marcus Aurelius Antoninus by George Long, M.A.

00:25.480 --> 00:31.880
Marcus Antoninus was born at Rome AD 121 on the 26th of April.

00:32.560 --> 00:38.440
His father Aeneas Verus died while he was praetor. His mother was Domitia Colvilla,

00:38.900 --> 00:45.840
also named Lucilla. The emperor Titus Antoninus Pius married Aenea Galeria Faustina,

00:46.300 --> 00:51.680
the sister of Aeneas Verus, and was consequently the uncle of Marcus Antoninus.

00:52.400 --> 00:57.920
When Hadrian adopted Antoninus Pius and declared him his successor in the empire,

00:58.580 --> 01:05.200
Antoninus Pius adopted both Lucius Sionius Commodus, the son of Aelius Caesar, and Marcus

01:05.200 --> 01:12.400
Antoninus, whose original name was Marcus Aeneas Verus. Antoninus then took the name of Marcus

01:12.400 --> 01:20.280
Aelius Aurelius Verus, to which was added the title of Caesar in AD 139. The name Aelius belonged

01:20.280 --> 01:27.160
to Hadrian's family, and Aurelius was the name of Antoninus Pius. When Marcus Antoninus became

01:27.160 --> 01:32.980
Augustus, he dropped the name of Verus and took the name of Antoninus. Accordingly,

01:33.060 --> 01:38.280
he is generally named Marcus Aurelius Antoninus, or simply Marcus Antoninus.

01:39.200 --> 01:44.440
The youth was most carefully brought up. He thanks the gods that he had good grandfathers,

01:44.440 --> 01:50.260
good parents, a good sister, good teachers, good associates, good kinsmen and friends,

01:50.740 --> 01:56.120
nearly everything good. He had the happy fortune to witness the example of his uncle

01:56.120 --> 02:02.440
and adoptive father Antoninus Pius, and he has recorded in his work the virtues of this excellent

02:02.440 --> 02:08.800
man and prudent ruler. Like many young Romans, he tried his hand at poetry and studied rhetoric.

02:09.360 --> 02:14.520
Herodes Atticus and Marcus Cornelius Fronto were his teachers in eloquence.

02:15.020 --> 02:19.820
There are extant letters between Fronto and Marcus, which show the great affection of the

02:19.820 --> 02:24.380
pupil for the master, and the master's great hopes of his industrious pupil.

02:26.280 --> 02:33.860
Marcus Corneliae Fontonis Reliquiae, Berlin 1816. There are a few letters between Fronto and

02:33.860 --> 02:42.000
Antoninus Pius. Marcus Antoninus mentions Fronto among those to whom he was indebted for his

02:42.000 --> 02:49.060
education. When he was 11 years old, he assumed the dress of philosophers, something plain and

02:49.060 --> 02:55.680
coarse, became a hard student, and lived a most laborious, abstemious life, even so far as to

02:55.680 --> 03:02.060
injure his health. Finally, he abandoned poetry and rhetoric for philosophy, and he attached

03:02.060 --> 03:08.520
himself to the sect the Stoics. But he did not neglect the study of law, which was a useful

03:08.520 --> 03:14.300
preparation for the high place which he was designed to fill. His teacher was Lucius Velassianus

03:14.300 --> 03:20.660
Mycenaeus, a distinguished jurist. We must suppose that he learned the Roman discipline of arms,

03:21.120 --> 03:26.780
which was a necessary part of the education of a man who afterwards led his troops to battle

03:26.780 --> 03:34.660
against a warlike race. Antoninus has recorded in his first book the names of his teachers and the

03:34.660 --> 03:39.720
obligations which he owed to each of them. The way in which he speaks of what he learned from them

03:39.720 --> 03:45.280
might seem to savor a vanity or self-praise if we look carelessly at the way in which he has

03:45.280 --> 03:51.200
expressed himself. But if anyone draws this conclusion, he will be mistaken. Antoninus

03:51.200 --> 03:55.880
means to commemorate the merits of his several teachers, what they taught, and what a pupil

03:55.880 --> 04:01.860
might learn from them. Besides, this book, like the eleven other books, was for his own use,

04:02.140 --> 04:06.780
and if we may trust the note at the end of the first book, it was written during one of Marcus

04:06.780 --> 04:11.980
Antoninus's campaigns against the Quadi, at a time when the commemoration of the virtues of

04:11.980 --> 04:17.300
his illustrious teachers might remind him of their lessons and the practical uses which he

04:17.300 --> 04:24.580
might derive from them. Among his teachers of philosophy was Sextus of Chaeronea, a grandson

04:24.580 --> 04:31.340
of Plutarch. What he learned from this excellent man is told by himself. His favorite teacher was

04:31.340 --> 04:37.460
Quintus Junius Rusticus, a philosopher and also a man of practical good sense in public affairs.

04:38.300 --> 04:43.820
Rusticus was the advisor of Antoninus after he became emperor. Young men who are destined

04:43.820 --> 04:49.620
for high places are not often fortunate in those who are about them, their companions and teachers.

04:50.110 --> 04:55.360
I do not know any example of a young prince having had an education which can be compared

04:55.360 --> 05:00.600
with that of Marcus Antoninus. Such a body of teachers, distinguished by their requirements

05:00.600 --> 05:06.620
and their character, will hardly be collected again, and as to the pupil, we have not had one

05:06.620 --> 05:17.020
like him since. Hadrian died in July AD 138 and was succeeded by Antoninus Pius. Marcus Antoninus

05:17.020 --> 05:24.440
married Faustina, his cousin, the daughter of Pius, probably about AD 146, for he had a daughter

05:24.440 --> 05:31.800
born in 147. He received from his adoptive father the title of Caesar and was associated with him

05:31.800 --> 05:36.980
in the administration of the state. The father and the adopted son lived together in perfect

05:36.980 --> 05:43.980
friendship and confidence. Antoninus was a dutiful son and the emperor Pius loved and esteemed him.

05:45.720 --> 05:53.700
Antoninus Pius died in March AD 161. The senate, it is said, urged Marcus Antoninus to take the

05:53.700 --> 05:59.500
sole administration of the empire, but he associated with himself the other adopted son of Pius,

05:59.900 --> 06:06.380
Lucius Sianius Commodus, who is generally called Lucius Verus. Thus Rome, for the first time,

06:06.540 --> 06:13.320
had two emperors. Verus was an indolent man of pleasure and unworthy of his station. Antoninus,

06:13.320 --> 06:18.380
however, bore with him and it is said that Verus had enough sense to pay his colleague the respect

06:18.380 --> 06:24.440
due to his character. A virtuous emperor and a loose partner lived together in peace and their

06:24.440 --> 06:31.320
alliance was strengthened by Antoninus giving to Verus for wife his daughter Lucilla. The reign of

06:31.320 --> 06:37.020
Antoninus was first troubled by a Parthian war in which Verus was sent to command, but he did

06:37.020 --> 06:42.340
nothing and the success that was obtained by the Romans in Armenia and on the Euphrates and Tigris

06:42.340 --> 06:50.480
was due to his generals. This Parthian war ended in AD 165. Aurelius and Verus had a triumph,

06:50.800 --> 06:56.860
AD 166, for the victories in the east. A pestilence followed which carried off great

06:56.860 --> 07:03.480
numbers in Rome and Italy and spread to the west of Europe. The north of Italy was also threatened

07:03.480 --> 07:08.760
by the rude people beyond the Alps from the borders of Gallia to the eastern side of the

07:08.760 --> 07:14.980
Adriatic. These barbarians attempted a break into Italy as the Germanic nations had attempted near

07:14.980 --> 07:20.960
300 years before and the rest of the life of Antoninus, with some intervals, was employed

07:20.960 --> 07:27.820
in driving back the invaders. In 169, Verus suddenly died and Antoninus administered the

07:27.820 --> 07:34.920
state alone. During the German wars, Antoninus resided for three years on the Danube at Carnuntum.

07:34.920 --> 07:40.040
The Marco Mani were driven out of Pannonia and almost destroyed in their retreat across the

07:40.040 --> 07:48.140
Danube and in AD 174 the emperor gained a great victory over the Quadi. In AD 175,

07:48.420 --> 07:54.000
Avidius Cassius, a brave and skillful Roman commander who was at the head of the troops in Asia,

07:54.840 --> 08:00.820
revolted and declared himself Augustus, but Cassius was assassinated by some of his officers

08:00.820 --> 08:06.700
and so the rebellion came to an end. Antoninus showed his humanity by his treatment of the

08:06.700 --> 08:12.620
family and the partisans of Cassius and his letter to the senate in which he recommends mercy is

08:12.620 --> 08:20.140
extant. Antoninus set out for the east on hearing of Cassius's revolt. Though he appears to have

08:20.140 --> 08:26.340
returned to Rome in AD 174, he went back to prosecute the war against the Germans and it

08:26.340 --> 08:32.900
probable that he marched direct to the east from the German war. His wife Faustina who accompanied

08:32.900 --> 08:38.500
him into Asia died suddenly at the foot of the Taurus to the great grief of her husband.

08:39.740 --> 08:45.840
Cappatilinus who has written the life of Antoninus and also Dion Cassius accused the empress of

08:45.840 --> 08:51.740
scandalous infidelity to her husband and of abominable lewdness, but Cappatilinus says

08:51.740 --> 08:58.260
Antoninus either knew it not or pretended not to know it. Nothing is so common as such malicious

08:58.260 --> 09:04.980
reports in all ages and the history of imperial Rome is full of them. Antoninus loved his wife

09:04.980 --> 09:11.520
and he says that she was obedient, affectionate, and simple. The same scandal had been spread about

09:11.520 --> 09:18.000
Faustina's mother, the wife of Antoninus Pius, and yet he too was perfectly satisfied with his wife.

09:19.000 --> 09:24.680
Antoninus Pius says after her death in a letter to Fronto that he would rather have lived in exile

09:24.680 --> 09:31.020
with his wife than in his palace at Rome without her. There are not many men who would give their

09:31.020 --> 09:37.020
wives a better character than these two emperors. Cappatilinus wrote in the time of Diocletian.

09:37.580 --> 09:43.780
He may have intended to tell the truth, but he is a poor feeble biographer. Dion Cassius,

09:43.780 --> 09:50.020
the most malignant of historians, always reports and perhaps he believed any scandal against anybody.

09:52.240 --> 09:58.040
Antoninus continued his journey to Syria and Egypt and on his return to Italy through Athens

09:58.040 --> 10:04.660
he was initiated into the Eleusinian Mysteries. It was the practice of the emperor to conform to

10:04.660 --> 10:09.420
the established rites of the age and to perform religious ceremonies with due solemnity.

10:10.060 --> 10:14.560
We cannot conclude from this that he was a superstitious man, though we might perhaps

10:14.560 --> 10:21.300
do so if his book did not show that he was not. But this is only one among many instances that

10:21.300 --> 10:27.200
a ruler's public acts do not always prove his real opinions. A prudent governor will not roughly

10:27.200 --> 10:31.960
oppose even the superstitions of his people, and though he may wish that they were wiser,

10:32.300 --> 10:35.660
he will know that he cannot make them so by offending their prejudices.

10:37.000 --> 10:42.620
Antoninus and his son Commodus entered Rome in triumph, perhaps for some German victories,

10:43.220 --> 10:49.960
on the 23rd of December AD 176. In the following year Commodus was associated with his father in

10:49.960 --> 10:58.060
the empire and took the name of Augustus. This year AD 177 is memorable in ecclesiastical history.

10:58.740 --> 11:03.600
Attalus and others were put to death at Lyon for their adherence to the Christian religion.

11:04.400 --> 11:09.680
The evidence of this persecution is a letter preserved by Eusebius. The letter is from the

11:09.680 --> 11:15.320
Christians of Vienna and Lugdunum in Gallia, Vienna and Lyon, to their Christian brethren

11:15.320 --> 11:21.720
in Asia and Phrygia, and it is preserved perhaps nearly entire. It contains a very

11:21.720 --> 11:26.600
particular description of the tortures inflicted on the Christians in Gallia, and it states that

11:26.600 --> 11:32.040
while the persecution was going on, Attalus, a Christian and a Roman citizen, was loudly

11:32.040 --> 11:37.560
demanded by the populace and brought into the amphitheater, but the governor ordered him to be

11:37.560 --> 11:42.320
reserved with the rest who were in prison, until he had received instructions from the emperor.

11:43.320 --> 11:46.860
Many had been tortured before the governor thought of applying to Antoninus.

11:47.480 --> 11:51.920
The imperial rescript says the letter was that the Christians should be punished,

11:52.320 --> 12:02.020
but if they would deny their faith they must be released. On this the work began again. The

12:02.900 --> 12:08.240
amphitheater. Some modern writers in ecclesiastical history, when they use this letter,

12:08.660 --> 12:11.500
say nothing of the wonderful stories of the martyr's sufferings.

12:12.340 --> 12:19.240
Sanctus, as the letter says, was burnt with plates of hot iron, till his body was one sore and he had

12:19.240 --> 12:24.920
lost all human form, but on being put to the rack he recovered his former appearance under the

12:24.920 --> 12:30.760
torture, which was thus a cure instead of a punishment. He was afterwards torn by beasts

12:30.760 --> 12:34.880
and placed on an iron chair and roasted. He died at last.

12:35.900 --> 12:40.820
The letter is one piece of evidence. The writer, whoever he was that wrote in the name of the

12:40.820 --> 12:46.320
Gallic Christians, is our evidence both for the ordinary and the extraordinary circumstances of

12:46.320 --> 12:52.720
the story, and we cannot accept his evidence for one part and reject the other. We often receive

12:52.720 --> 12:57.660
small evidence as a proof of a thing which we believe to be within the limits of probability

12:57.660 --> 13:04.020
or possibility, and we reject exactly the same evidence when the thing to which it refers appears

13:04.020 --> 13:10.740
very improbable or impossible. But this is a false method of inquiry, though it is followed by some

13:10.740 --> 13:15.360
modern writers, who select what they like from a story and reject the rest of the evidence,

13:15.900 --> 13:21.220
or if they do not reject it they dishonestly suppress it. A man can only act consistently

13:21.220 --> 13:26.040
by accepting all this letter or rejecting it all, and we cannot blame him for either.

13:26.600 --> 13:31.160
But he who rejects it may still admit that such a letter may be founded on real facts,

13:31.700 --> 13:36.180
and he would make this admission as the most probable way of accounting for the existence

13:36.180 --> 13:42.020
of the letter. But if, as he would suppose, the writer has stated some things falsely,

13:42.300 --> 13:44.900
he cannot tell what part of his story is worthy of credit.

13:46.060 --> 13:50.920
The war on the northern frontier appears to have been uninterrupted during the visit of Antoninus

13:50.920 --> 13:56.060
to the east, and on his return the emperor again left Rome to oppose the barbarians.

13:56.780 --> 14:02.980
The Germanic people were defeated in a great battle AD 179. During this campaign the emperor

14:02.980 --> 14:09.520
was seized with some contagious malady, of which he died in the camp at Sirmium, Mitrovitz, on the

14:09.520 --> 14:16.740
Sava in Lower Pannonia, but at Vindabena, Vienna, according to other authorities, on the 17th March

14:16.740 --> 14:24.700
AD 180, in the 59th year of his age. His son Commodus was with him. The body or the ashes,

14:24.800 --> 14:29.220
probably of the emperor, were carried to Rome, and he received the honor of deification.

14:30.120 --> 14:34.640
Those who could afford it had his statue or bust, and when Cuppatilinus wrote,

14:34.980 --> 14:40.340
many people still had statues of Antoninus among the Deipinates, or household deities.

14:41.000 --> 14:45.720
He was in a manner made a saint. Commodus erected to the memory of his father the

14:45.720 --> 14:52.040
Antonine Column, which is now in the Piazza Colonna at Rome. The bas reliefs, which are

14:52.040 --> 14:56.660
placed in a spiral line around the shaft, commemorate the victories of Antoninus over

14:56.660 --> 15:01.780
the Marcomanni and the Quatti, and the miraculous shower of rain which refreshed the Roman soldiers

15:01.780 --> 15:07.480
and discomfited their enemies. The statue of Antoninus was placed on the capital of the Column,

15:07.800 --> 15:12.760
but it was removed at some time unknown, and a bronze statue of Saint Paul was put in the

15:12.760 --> 15:19.420
place of Pope Sixtus V. The historical evidence for the times of Antoninus is very defective,

15:19.860 --> 15:25.220
and some of that which remains is not credible. The most curious is the story about the miracle

15:25.220 --> 15:32.520
which happened in AD 174 during the war with the Quatti. The Roman army was in danger of perishing

15:32.520 --> 15:38.920
by thirst, but a sudden storm drenched them with rain, while it discharged fire and hail on their

15:38.920 --> 15:44.340
enemies, and the Romans gained a great victory. All the authorities which speak of the battle

15:44.340 --> 15:50.000
speak also of the miracle. The Gentile writers assigned it to their gods, and the Christians

15:50.000 --> 15:54.680
to the intercession of the Christian legion and the emperor's army. To confirm the Christian

15:54.680 --> 16:00.200
statement, it is added that the emperor gave the title of thundering to this legion, but Dossier

16:00.200 --> 16:04.840
and others who maintain the Christian report of the miracle admit that this title of thundering

16:04.840 --> 16:09.420
or lightning was not given to this legion because the Quatti were struck with lightning,

16:09.860 --> 16:14.120
but because there was a figure of lightning on their shields, and that this title of the

16:14.120 --> 16:19.800
legion existed in the time of Augustus. Scaliger also had observed that the legion was called

16:19.800 --> 16:25.720
thundering before the reign of Antoninus. We can learn this from Dion Cassius, who enumerates all

16:25.720 --> 16:31.580
the legions of Augustus's time. The name thundering or lightning also occurs on an inscription of the

16:31.580 --> 16:38.640
Trajan, which was found at Trieste. Eusebius, when he relates the miracle, quotes Apollinarius,

16:39.020 --> 16:44.640
bishop of Hierapolis, as authority for this name being given to the legion Melitini by the emperor

16:44.640 --> 16:49.860
in consequence of the success which he had obtained through their prayers, from which we may estimate

16:49.860 --> 16:55.440
the value of Apollinarius's testimony. Eusebius does not say in what book of Apollinarius the

16:55.440 --> 17:00.860
statement occurs. Dion says that the thundering legion was stationed in Cappadocia in the time

17:00.860 --> 17:06.140
of Augustus. Velasius also observes that in the notitia of the Imperium Romanum,

17:06.620 --> 17:10.940
there is mentioned under the commander of Armenia the prefectura of the 12th legion

17:10.940 --> 17:16.300
named thundering Melitini, and this position in Armenia will agree with what Dion says of

17:16.300 --> 17:22.200
its position in Cappadocia. Accordingly, Velasius concludes that Melitini was not the name of the

17:22.200 --> 17:28.540
legion, but of the town in which it was stationed. Melitini was also the name of the district in which

17:28.540 --> 17:33.620
this town was situated. The legions did not, he says, take their name from the place where they

17:33.620 --> 17:39.180
were on duty, but from the country in which they were raised, and therefore what Eusebius says about

17:39.180 --> 17:44.900
the Melitini does not seem probable to him. Yet Velasius, on the authority of Apollinarius and

17:44.900 --> 17:49.160
Tertullian, believed that the miracle was worked through the prayers of the Christian soldiers and

17:49.160 --> 17:54.680
the emperor's army. Rufinus does not give the name of Melitini to this legion, says Velasius,

17:54.680 --> 18:00.080
and probably he purposely omitted it, because he knew that Melitini was the name of a town in

18:00.080 --> 18:06.960
Armenia Minor, where the legion was stationed in his time. The emperor, it is said, made a report

18:06.960 --> 18:12.680
of his victory to the senate, which we may believe, for such was the practice. But we do not know what

18:12.680 --> 18:17.840
he said in his letter, for it is not extant. Dossier assumes that the emperor's letter was

18:17.840 --> 18:23.580
purposely destroyed by the senate, or the enemies of Christianity, that so honorable a testimony to

18:23.580 --> 18:29.560
Christians and their religion might not be perpetuated. The critic has, however, not seen

18:29.560 --> 18:34.700
that he contradicts when he tells us purported the letter, for he says that it was destroyed,

18:35.160 --> 18:40.620
and even Eusebius could not find it. But there does exist a letter in Greek addressed by Antoninus

18:40.620 --> 18:46.340
to the Roman people and the sacred senate after this memorable victory. It is sometimes printed

18:46.340 --> 18:51.960
after Justin's first apology, but is totally unconnected with the apologies. This letter is

18:51.960 --> 18:56.480
one of the most stupid forgeries of the many which exist, and it cannot be possibly founded

18:56.480 --> 19:01.360
even on the genuine report of Antoninus to the senate. If it were genuine, it would free the

19:01.360 --> 19:06.160
emperor from the charge of persecuting men because they were Christians. For he says in this false

19:06.160 --> 19:11.520
letter that if a man accused another only of being a Christian, and the accused confess and there is

19:11.520 --> 19:17.200
nothing else against him, he must be set free. With this monstrous addition, made by a man

19:17.200 --> 19:24.780
inconceivably ignorant, that the informer must be burnt alive. During the time of Antoninus Pius

19:24.780 --> 19:30.620
and Marcus Antoninus, there appeared the first apology of Justinus, and under Marcus Antoninus

19:30.620 --> 19:35.500
the oration of Tatian against the Greeks, which was a fierce attack on the established religions.

19:36.340 --> 19:42.140
The address of Athenagoras to Marcus Antoninus on behalf of the Christians and the apology of

19:42.140 --> 19:47.460
Plato, Bishop of Sardis, also addressed to the emperor and that of Apollinarius.

19:48.360 --> 19:54.280
The first apology of Justinus is addressed to Titus Antoninus Pius and his two adopted sons,

19:54.520 --> 19:58.830
Marcus Antoninus and Lucius Verus, but we do not know whether they read it.

19:59.580 --> 20:05.260
Footnote, Aureus says that Justinus the philosopher presented to Antoninus Pius his

20:05.260 --> 20:09.360
work in defense of the Christian religion, and made him merciful to the Christians.

20:09.920 --> 20:10.980
End footnote.

20:11.980 --> 20:15.900
The second apology of Justinus is entitled To the Roman Senate,

20:16.420 --> 20:22.760
but this superscription is from some copyist. In the first chapter Justinus addresses the Romans.

20:23.340 --> 20:28.260
In the second chapter he speaks of an affair that had recently happened in the time of Marcus

20:28.260 --> 20:37.580
Antoninus and Lucius Verus as it seems, and he also directly addresses the emperor, saying of

20:37.580 --> 20:40.120
emperor, and thou didst grant the petition.

20:41.580 --> 20:46.900
In other passages the writer addresses the two emperors, from which we must conclude that the

20:46.900 --> 20:52.020
apology was directed to them. Eusebius states that the second apology was addressed to the

20:52.020 --> 20:58.240
successor of Antoninus Pius, and he names him Antoninus Verus, meaning Marcus Antoninus.

20:58.840 --> 21:04.860
In one passage of the second apology, Justinus, or the writer whoever he may be, says that even

21:04.860 --> 21:09.380
men who followed the Stoic doctrines when they ordered their lives according to ethical reason

21:09.380 --> 21:16.100
were hated and murdered, such as Heraclitus, Musonius in his own times, and others. For all

21:16.100 --> 21:21.200
those who in any way labored to live according to reason and avoided wickedness were always hated,

21:21.660 --> 21:23.920
and this was the effect of the work of demons.

21:25.480 --> 21:34.520
Justinus himself is said to have been put to death at Rome because he refused to sacrifice to the

21:34.520 --> 21:40.440
states, nor in the time of Antoninus Pius, if the second apology was written in the time of Marcus

21:40.440 --> 21:46.200
Antoninus, and there was evidence that this event took place under Marcus Antoninus and Lucius Verus,

21:46.400 --> 21:48.460
when Rusticus was prefect of the city.

21:49.840 --> 21:55.360
The persecution in which Polycarp suffered at Smyrna belongs to the time of Marcus Antoninus.

21:55.800 --> 22:04.500
The evidence for it is the letter of the church of Smyrna to the churches of Philomelium and the

22:04.500 --> 22:07.860
But the critics do not agree about the time of Polycarp's death,

22:08.260 --> 22:11.060
differing in the two extremes to the amount of 12 years.

22:11.880 --> 22:16.800
The circumstances of Polycarp's martyrdom were accompanied by miracles, one of which Eusebius

22:16.800 --> 22:22.000
has omitted, but it appears in the oldest Latin version of the letter, which Usher published,

22:22.280 --> 22:25.940
and it is supposed that this version was made not long after the time of Eusebius.

22:26.620 --> 22:30.320
The notice at the end of the letter states that it was transcribed by Caius,

22:30.320 --> 22:36.500
from the copy of Irenaeus, the disciple of Polycarp, then transcribed by Socrates at Corinth,

22:37.820 --> 22:41.520
after which I, Pioneus, again wrote it out from the copy above mentioned,

22:41.960 --> 22:46.640
having searched it out by the revelation of Polycarp, who directed it to me, etc.

22:48.480 --> 22:52.320
The story of Polycarp's martyrdom is embellished with miraculous circumstances

22:52.320 --> 22:56.980
which some modern writers on ecclesiastical history take the liberty of omitting.

22:57.860 --> 22:58.460
Footnote.

22:58.720 --> 23:03.780
Conyers Middleton, An Inquiry into the Miraculous Powers, etc. page 126.

23:04.720 --> 23:09.660
Middleton says that Eusebius omitted to mention the dove, which flew out of Polycarp's body,

23:10.100 --> 23:12.760
and Dodwell and Archbishop Wake have done the same.

23:13.300 --> 23:18.300
Wake says, I am so little a friend to such miracles that I thought it better with Eusebius

23:18.300 --> 23:23.020
to omit that circumstance than to mention it from Bishop Usher's manuscript.

23:24.380 --> 23:29.660
Which manuscript, however, says Middleton, he afterwards declares to be so well attested

23:29.660 --> 23:32.680
that we need not any further assurance of the truth of it.

23:33.320 --> 23:34.200
End footnote.

23:35.620 --> 23:40.140
In order to form a proper notion of the condition of the Christians under Marcus Antoninus,

23:40.480 --> 23:42.340
we must go back to Trajan's time.

23:42.920 --> 23:47.580
When the younger Pliny was governor of Bithynia, the Christians were numerous in those parts,

23:47.940 --> 23:50.520
and the worshippers of the old religion were falling off.

23:50.520 --> 23:53.880
The temples were deserted, the festivals neglected,

23:54.360 --> 23:56.760
and there were no purchasers of victims for sacrifice.

23:57.720 --> 24:00.400
Those who were interested in the maintenance of the old religion

24:00.400 --> 24:02.740
thus found that their prophets were in danger.

24:03.620 --> 24:07.460
Christians of both sexes and of all ages were brought before the governor,

24:07.800 --> 24:09.140
who did not know what to do with them.

24:09.660 --> 24:11.900
He could come to know their conclusion in this,

24:12.200 --> 24:16.900
that those who confess to be Christians and persevered in their religion ought to be punished,

24:17.320 --> 24:19.920
if for nothing else for their invincible obstinacy.

24:20.520 --> 24:23.260
He found no crimes proved against the Christians,

24:23.720 --> 24:27.720
and he could only characterize their religion as a depraved and extravagant superstition,

24:28.100 --> 24:31.580
which might be stopped if the people are allowed the opportunity of recanting.

24:32.300 --> 24:34.380
Pliny wrote this in a letter to Trajan.

24:34.720 --> 24:35.260
Footnote.

24:35.560 --> 24:39.680
The Martyrium Ignatii, first published in Latin by Archbishop Usher,

24:40.120 --> 24:43.340
is the chief evidence for the circumstances of Ignatius's death.

24:43.980 --> 24:44.700
End footnote.

24:45.800 --> 24:49.400
In the time of Hadrian, it was no longer possible for the Roman government

24:49.400 --> 24:54.320
to overlook the great increase of the Christians and the hostility of the common sort to them.

24:55.080 --> 24:57.920
If the governors in the provinces were willing to let them alone,

24:58.260 --> 25:01.000
they could not resist the fanaticism of the heathen community,

25:01.440 --> 25:03.680
who looked on the Christians as atheists.

25:04.340 --> 25:07.140
The Jews, too, who were settled all over the Roman Empire,

25:07.540 --> 25:10.580
were as hostile to the Christians as the Gentiles were.

25:11.240 --> 25:11.720
Footnote.

25:11.920 --> 25:14.400
We have the evidence of Justinus to this effect.

25:15.180 --> 25:19.060
The Christians are attacked by the Jews as if they were men of a different race,

25:19.060 --> 25:21.040
and are persecuted by the Greeks,

25:21.580 --> 25:24.260
and those who hate them cannot give the reason of their enmity.

25:25.780 --> 25:26.820
End footnote.

25:27.860 --> 25:30.540
With the time of Hadrian began the Christian apologies,

25:31.120 --> 25:34.640
which show plainly what the popular feeling towards the Christians then was.

25:35.480 --> 25:39.920
A re-script of Hadrian to Manutius Fundanus, the proconsul of Asia,

25:40.320 --> 25:42.560
which stands at the end of Justin's first apology,

25:43.200 --> 25:45.900
instructs the governor that innocent people must not be troubled,

25:45.900 --> 25:49.260
and false accusers must not be allowed to extort money from them.

25:49.920 --> 25:52.820
The charges against the Christians must be made in due form,

25:53.280 --> 25:55.760
and no attention must be paid to popular clamors.

25:56.220 --> 25:59.780
When Christians were regularly prosecuted and convicted of illegal acts,

26:00.180 --> 26:02.520
they must be punished according to their deserts,

26:02.700 --> 26:04.840
and false accusers also must be punished.

26:05.480 --> 26:05.980
Footnote.

26:06.380 --> 26:11.520
And in Eusebius, Erosius says that Hadrian sent this re-script to Manutius Fundanus,

26:11.740 --> 26:12.780
proconsul of Asia,

26:12.780 --> 26:17.300
after being instructed in books written on the Christian religion by Quadratus,

26:17.740 --> 26:19.080
a disciple of the apostles,

26:19.660 --> 26:22.940
and Aristides, an Athenian, an honest and wise man,

26:23.480 --> 26:24.880
and Serenus Grineus.

26:25.480 --> 26:27.660
In the Greek text of Hadrian's re-script,

26:28.040 --> 26:32.500
there is mentioned Serenius Grineanus, the predecessor of Manutius Fundanus,

26:32.940 --> 26:34.260
in the government of Asia.

26:34.860 --> 26:39.020
This re-script of Hadrian has clearly been added to the apology by some editor.

26:39.680 --> 26:40.420
End footnote.

26:41.700 --> 26:45.260
Antonius Pius is said to have published re-scripts to the same effect.

26:45.780 --> 26:49.580
The terms of Hadrian's re-script seem very favorable to the Christians,

26:50.180 --> 26:51.980
but if we understand it in this sense,

26:52.280 --> 26:55.120
that they were only to be punished like other people for illegal acts,

26:55.580 --> 26:56.700
it would have no meaning,

26:57.160 --> 26:59.760
for that could have been done without asking the emperor's advice.

27:00.300 --> 27:03.480
The real purpose of the re-script is that Christians must be punished

27:03.480 --> 27:05.060
if they persisted in their belief,

27:05.520 --> 27:09.020
and would not prove their renunciation of it by acknowledging the heathen religion.

27:09.560 --> 27:11.240
This was Trajan's rule,

27:11.640 --> 27:14.080
and we have no reason for supposing that Hadrian

27:14.080 --> 27:16.500
granted more to the Christians than Trajan did.

27:17.140 --> 27:20.260
There is also printed at the end of Justin's first apology,

27:20.780 --> 27:24.420
a re-script of Antoninus Pius to the commune of Asia,

27:24.920 --> 27:26.660
and it is also in Eusebius.

27:27.060 --> 27:30.600
The date of the re-script is the third consulship of Antoninus Pius.

27:31.060 --> 27:33.820
The re-script declares that the Christians, for they are meant,

27:34.280 --> 27:36.800
though the name Christians does not occur in the re-script,

27:36.800 --> 27:41.000
were not to be disturbed unless they were attempting something against the Roman rule,

27:41.400 --> 27:44.040
and no man was to be punished simply for being a Christian.

27:44.880 --> 27:46.560
But this re-script is spurious.

27:47.100 --> 27:49.960
Any man moderately acquainted with Roman history

27:49.960 --> 27:54.320
will see by the style and tenor that it is a clumsy forgery.

27:56.020 --> 27:57.800
In the time of Marcus Antoninus,

27:57.920 --> 28:01.220
the opposition between the old and the new belief was still stronger,

28:01.740 --> 28:04.820
and the adherents of the heathen religion urged those in authority

28:04.820 --> 28:08.860
to a more regular resistance to the invasions of the Christian faith.

28:09.840 --> 28:12.520
Melito, in his apology to Marcus Antoninus,

28:12.920 --> 28:16.820
represents the Christians of Asia as persecuted under new imperial orders.

28:17.500 --> 28:21.720
Shameless informers, he says, men who were greedy after the property of others,

28:22.340 --> 28:25.700
used these orders as a means of robbing those who were doing no harm.

28:26.500 --> 28:29.940
He doubts if a just emperor could have ordered anything so unjust,

28:30.480 --> 28:32.920
and if the last order was really not from the emperor,

28:32.920 --> 28:35.960
the Christians entreat him not to give them up to their enemies.

28:36.840 --> 28:40.260
We conclude from this that there were at least imperial re-scripts

28:40.260 --> 28:45.360
or constitutions of Marcus Antoninus which were made the foundations of these persecutions.

28:45.960 --> 28:49.000
The fact of being a Christian was now a crime and punished

28:49.000 --> 28:51.300
unless the accused denied their religion.

28:52.120 --> 28:57.900
Then come the persecutions at Smyrna, which some modern critics place in AD 167,

28:58.120 --> 29:00.340
ten years before the persecution of Lyon.

29:00.340 --> 29:04.920
The governors of the provinces under Marcus Antoninus might have found enough

29:04.920 --> 29:08.520
even in Trajan's re-script to warrant them in punishing Christians,

29:09.140 --> 29:13.720
and the fanaticism of the people would drive them to persecution even if they were unwilling.

29:14.700 --> 29:18.380
But besides the fact of the Christians rejecting all the heathen ceremonies,

29:18.980 --> 29:23.200
we must not forget that they plainly maintained that all the heathen religions were false.

29:23.820 --> 29:26.640
The Christians thus declared war against the heathen rights,

29:26.640 --> 29:31.920
and it is hardly necessary to observe that this was a declaration of hostility against

29:31.920 --> 29:36.440
the Roman government, which tolerated all the various forms of superstition that existed in

29:36.440 --> 29:41.720
the empire and could not consistently tolerate another religion, which declared that all the

29:41.720 --> 29:46.640
rest were false, and all the splendid ceremonies of the empire only a worship of devils.

29:47.700 --> 29:53.300
If we had a true ecclesiastical history, we should know how the Roman empires attempted to

29:53.300 --> 29:57.420
the new religion, how they enforced their principle of finally punishing Christians,

29:57.880 --> 30:02.280
simply as Christians, which Justin in his apology affirms that they did,

30:02.580 --> 30:08.140
and I have no doubt that he tells the truth. How far popular clamor and riots went in this matter,

30:08.560 --> 30:12.720
and how far many fanatical and ignorant Christians, for there were many such,

30:13.140 --> 30:16.680
contributed to excite the fanaticism on the other side and to

30:16.680 --> 30:19.340
embedder the quarrel between the Roman government and the new religion.

30:20.120 --> 30:26.560
Our extant ecclesiastical histories are manifestly falsified, and what truth they contain is grossly

30:26.560 --> 30:32.480
exaggerated, but the fact is certain that in the time of Marcus Antoninus the heathen populations

30:32.480 --> 30:38.280
were an open hostility to the Christians, and that under Antoninus' rule men were put to death

30:38.280 --> 30:43.980
because they were Christians. Eusebius in the preface to his fifth book remarks that in the

30:43.980 --> 30:48.880
seventeenth year of Antoninus' reign in some parts of the world the persecution of the Christians

30:48.880 --> 30:54.820
became more violent and that it proceeded from the populace in the cities, and he adds in his

30:54.820 --> 31:00.860
usual style of exaggeration that we may infer from what took place in a single nation that myriads

31:00.860 --> 31:05.820
of martyrs were made in the habitable earth. The nation which he alludes to is Gallia,

31:06.180 --> 31:09.980
and he then proceeds to give the letter to the churches of Vienna and Lugdunum.

31:10.380 --> 31:18.720
It is probable that he has assigned the true cause of the persecutions, the fanaticism of

31:18.720 --> 31:24.100
with these disturbances. How far Marcus was cognizant of these cruel proceedings we do not

31:24.100 --> 31:29.340
know, for the historical records of his reign are very defective. He did not make the rule

31:29.340 --> 31:33.780
against the Christians, for Trajan did that, and if we admit that he would have been willing to let

31:33.780 --> 31:39.220
the Christians alone we cannot affirm that he was in his power, for it would be a great mistake to

31:39.220 --> 31:45.320
suppose that Antoninus had the unlimited authority which some modern sovereigns have had. His power

31:45.320 --> 31:50.660
was limited by certain constitutional forms, by the senate, and by the precedence of his predecessors.

31:51.560 --> 31:55.880
We cannot admit that such a man was an active persecutor, for there is no evidence that he

31:55.880 --> 32:00.820
was, though it is certain that he had no good opinion of the Christians, as appears from his

32:00.820 --> 32:07.560
own words. Footnote. Except that of Erosius, who says that during the Parthian War there were

32:07.560 --> 32:12.100
grievous persecutions of the Christians in Asia and Gallia under the orders of Marcus,

32:12.680 --> 32:20.040
prakepto aeius, and, quote, many were crowned with the martyrdom of saints, unquote. End footnote.

32:21.140 --> 32:26.420
But he knew nothing of them except their hostility to the Roman religion, and he probably thought

32:26.420 --> 32:31.060
that they were dangerous to the state, notwithstanding the professions false or true of some of the

32:31.060 --> 32:37.700
apologists. So much I have said, because it would be unfair not to state all that can be urged

32:37.700 --> 32:43.460
against a man whom his contemporaries in subsequent ages venerated as a model of virtue

32:43.460 --> 32:49.660
and benevolence. If I admitted the genuineness of some documents, he would be altogether clear

32:49.660 --> 32:55.380
from the charge of even allowing any persecutions. But as I seek the truth and am sure that they are

32:55.380 --> 33:02.720
false, I leave him to bear whatever blame is his due. Footnote. Dr. F.C. Bower, in his work entitled,

33:08.960 --> 33:12.380
etc., has examined this question with great good sense and fairness,

33:12.820 --> 33:16.880
and I believe he has stated the truth as near as our authorities enable us to reach it.

33:17.840 --> 33:23.480
End footnote. I add that it is quite certain that Antoninus did not derive any of his ethical

33:23.480 --> 33:37.680
principles from a religion of which he knew nothing. Footnote. In the digest there is the

33:50.900 --> 34:03.320
In the first book he speaks of himself, his family, and his teachers, and in other books

34:03.320 --> 34:10.400
himself. Suedas notices the work of Antoninus in 12 books, which he names the conduct of his own

34:10.400 --> 34:15.780
life, and he cites the book under several words in his dictionary, giving the emperor's name,

34:15.840 --> 34:21.080
but not the title of the work. There are also passages cited by Suedas from Antoninus

34:21.080 --> 34:26.000
without mention of the emperor's name. The true title of the work is unknown.

34:27.080 --> 34:31.860
Zylander, who published the first edition of this book with a Latin version, used a manuscript

34:31.860 --> 34:36.180
which contained the 12 books, but it is not known where the manuscript is now.

34:37.080 --> 34:43.100
The only other complete manuscript which is known to exist is in the Vatican Library, but it has

34:43.100 --> 34:47.900
no titles and no inscriptions of the several books. The 11th only has the inscription

34:47.900 --> 34:53.960
marked with an asterisk. The other Vatican manuscripts in the 3 Florentine contain only

34:53.960 --> 34:59.020
excerpts from the emperor's book. All the titles of the excerpts nearly agree with that which

34:59.020 --> 35:05.280
Zylander prefixed to his edition. This title has been used by all subsequent editors. We cannot

35:05.280 --> 35:10.860
tell whether Antoninus divided his work into books or somebody else did it. If the inscriptions at

35:10.860 --> 35:15.100
the end of the first and second books are genuine, he may have made the division himself.

35:15.920 --> 35:20.560
It is plain that the emperor wrote down his thoughts or reflections as the occasions arose,

35:20.980 --> 35:29.000
and since they were intended for his own use, it is no improbable conjecture that he left a

35:29.000 --> 35:32.980
manuscript, for it is not likely that so diligent a man would use the labor of a

35:32.980 --> 35:38.040
transcriber for such a purpose and expose his most secret thoughts to any other eye.

35:38.920 --> 35:44.120
He may have also intended the book for his son Eusebius Commodus, who however had no taste for

35:44.120 --> 35:49.920
his father's philosophy. Some careful hand preserved the precious volume, and a work by

35:49.920 --> 35:56.380
Antoninus is mentioned by other late writers besides Suidas. Many critics have labored on

35:57.220 --> 36:04.440
Antoninus. The most complete edition is that by Thomas Gattacher, 1652, quarto. The second edition

36:04.440 --> 36:11.720
of Gattacher was superintended by George Stanep, 1697, quarto. There is also an edition of 1704.

36:12.680 --> 36:17.580
Gattacher made and suggested many good corrections, and he also made a new Latin version,

36:17.880 --> 36:22.720
which is not a very good specimen of Latin, but it generally expresses the sense of the original,

36:22.720 --> 36:28.380
and often better than some of the more recent translations. He added in the margin opposite

36:28.380 --> 36:33.760
to each paragraph references to the other parallel passages, and he wrote a commentary,

36:34.160 --> 36:39.200
one of the most complete that has been written on any ancient author. This commentary contains

36:39.200 --> 36:44.240
the editor's exposition of the more difficult passages, and quotations from all the Greek and

36:44.240 --> 36:49.780
Roman writers for the illustration of the text. It is a wonderful monument of learning and labor,

36:49.780 --> 36:53.360
and certainly no Englishman has yet done anything like it.

36:53.880 --> 36:58.920
At the end of his preface, the editor says that he wrote it at Rotherhiss, near London in a severe

36:58.920 --> 37:06.520
winter, when he was in the 78th year of his age, 1651, a time when Milton, Seldon, and other great

37:06.520 --> 37:12.280
men of the Commonwealth time were living, and the great French scholar Somaz, Salmatius, with whom

37:12.280 --> 37:18.460
Gattacher corresponded and received help from him for his edition of Antoninus. The Greek text has

37:18.460 --> 37:25.880
also been edited by J.M. Schultz, Leipzig 1802, 8 volumes, and by the learned Greek Athamantinous

37:25.880 --> 37:33.540
Corais, Paris 1816, 8 volumes. The text of Schultz was republished by Tauchnitz, 1821.

37:34.500 --> 37:40.180
There are English, German, French, Italian, and Spanish translations of Marcus Antoninus,

37:40.300 --> 37:46.180
and there may be others. I have not seen all the English translations. There is one by Jeremy

37:46.180 --> 37:53.300
Collier, 1702, 8 volumes, a most coarse and vulgar copy of the original. The latest French

37:53.300 --> 37:59.520
translation by Alexis Pierron, in the collection of Charpentier, is better than Dossier's,

37:59.540 --> 38:07.280
which has been honored with an Italian version, Oudinay, 1772. There is an Italian version, 1675,

38:07.760 --> 38:14.420
which I have not seen. It is by a cardinal. Quote, A man illustrious in the church, the cardinal

38:14.420 --> 38:20.380
Francis Barberini the Elder, nephew of Pope Urban VII, occupied the last years of his life in

38:20.380 --> 38:25.320
translating into his native language the thoughts of the Roman emperor, in order to diffuse among

38:25.320 --> 38:32.020
the faithful the fertilizing and vivifying seeds. He dedicated this translation to his soul, to make

38:32.020 --> 38:37.320
it, as he says in his energetic style, redder than his purple at the sight of the virtues of this

38:37.320 --> 38:38.040
Gentile.

38:40.680 --> 38:45.820
I have made this translation at intervals, after having used the book for many years.

38:46.440 --> 38:51.120
It is made from the Greek, but I have not always followed one text, and I have occasionally

38:51.120 --> 38:57.220
compared other versions with my own. I made this translation for my own use, because I found that

38:57.220 --> 39:02.200
it was worth the labor, but it may be useful to others also, and therefore I determined to print

39:02.200 --> 39:08.280
it. As the original is sometimes very difficult to understand, and still more difficult to

39:08.280 --> 39:14.200
translate, it is not possible that I have always avoided error. But I believe that I have not often

39:14.200 --> 39:18.200
missed the meaning, and those who will take the trouble to compare the translation with the

39:18.200 --> 39:24.120
original should not hastily conclude that I am wrong if they do not agree with me. Some passages

39:24.120 --> 39:29.500
do give the meaning, though at first sight they may not appear to do so, and when I differ from

39:29.500 --> 39:35.240
I think in some places they are wrong, and in other places I am sure that they are.

39:35.800 --> 39:41.080
I have placed in some passages a plus sign, which indicates corruption in the text or great

39:41.080 --> 39:46.440
uncertainty in the meaning. I could have made the language more easy and flowing, but I have

39:46.440 --> 39:51.540
preferred a ruder style as being better suited to express the character of the original, and

39:51.540 --> 39:58.840
sometimes the obscurity which may appear in the version is a fair copy of the obscurity of the

39:58.840 --> 40:04.180
I have done the best that I could, and in the next text I have always given the same translation

40:04.180 --> 40:10.140
of the same word. The last reflection of the stoic philosophy that I have observed

40:10.140 --> 40:17.200
is in Simplicius's Commentary of the Incaridion of Epictetus. Simplicius was not a Christian,

40:17.940 --> 40:23.200
and such a man was not likely to be converted at a time when Christianity was grossly corrupted.

40:23.840 --> 40:29.060
But he was a really religious man, and he includes his commentary with a prayer to the deity,

40:29.500 --> 40:36.840
which no Christian could improve. From the time of Zeno to Simplicius, a period of about 900 years,

40:37.260 --> 40:41.300
the stoic philosophy formed the characters of some of the best and greatest men.

40:41.940 --> 40:47.060
Finally it became extinct, and we hear no more of it till the revival of letters in Italy.

40:48.120 --> 40:54.700
Angelo Poliziano met with two very inaccurate and incomplete manuscripts of Epictetus's

40:54.700 --> 41:00.660
Incaridion, which he had translated into Latin and dedicated to his great patron Lorenzo de Medici,

41:01.200 --> 41:05.700
in whose collection he had found the book. Poliziano's version was printed in the first

41:05.700 --> 41:13.620
ball edition of the Incaridion, AD 1531, op. Andraeum cartondrum. Poliziano recommends the

41:13.620 --> 41:19.500
Incaridion to Lorenzo as a work well suited to his temper, and useful in the difficulties

41:19.500 --> 41:26.180
by which he was surrounded. Epictetus and Antoninus have had readers ever since they were printed.

41:26.960 --> 41:32.120
The little book of Antoninus has been the companion of some great men. Machiavelli's

41:32.120 --> 41:37.180
Art of War and Marcus Antoninus were the two books which were used when he was a young man

41:37.180 --> 41:42.040
by Captain John Smith, and he could not have found two writers better fitted to form the

41:42.040 --> 41:48.500
of a soldier and a man. Smith is almost unknown and forgotten in England, his native country,

41:48.820 --> 41:54.780
but not in America where he saved the young colony of Virginia. He was great in his heroic mind and

41:54.780 --> 42:00.400
his deeds and arms, but greater still in the nobleness of his character. For a man's greatness

42:00.400 --> 42:06.400
lies not in wealth and station, as the vulgar believe, nor yet in his intellectual capacity,

42:06.800 --> 42:11.980
which is often associated with the meanest moral character, the most abject servility to those in

42:11.980 --> 42:18.760
high places, and arrogance to the poor lowly. But a man's true greatness lies in the consciousness

42:18.760 --> 42:24.100
of an honest purpose in life, founded on a just estimate of himself and everything else,

42:24.540 --> 42:30.140
on frequent self-examination, and a steady obedience to the rule which he knows to be right,

42:30.480 --> 42:36.640
without troubling himself, as the emperor says he should not, about what others may think or say,

42:36.640 --> 42:42.180
or whether they do or do not do, that which he thinks and says and does.

